Pruning the corpus makes SpamSieve run faster and reduces the amount of memory and disk space that it needs. Pruning does not increase SpamSieve’s accuracy, and excessive pruning will actually reduce it.

SpamSieve 2.0 uses new file formats for storing the corpus and statistics. Your old data can be automatically converted to the new formats. To take best advantage of SpamSieve 2.0’s improved accuracy, it is recommended that you use the Reset Corpus command to erase your old corpus and that you then retrain SpamSieve using your saved messages. However, this is only a recommendation, and you may continue using your old corpus if you do not have many saved spam and good messages with which to retrain SpamSieve.

SpamSieve relies on a corpus of your mail in order to determine whether incoming messages are spam. Before you begin using SpamSieve, you should train it with some messages, both good ones and spam.
A few hundred messages are enough to get good accuracy, and you can use up to 1,000 in the initial training. It’s OK if you don’t have that many messages; just use what you have.
About 65% of the messages in the initial training should be spam, as shown at the bottom of the Statistics window. It is better to train SpamSieve with fewer messages than to stray far from this target ratio.
After the initial training, SpamSieve will continue to learn as you correct its mistakes and as it observes your incoming mail.
For more information on training SpamSieve and on configuring your e-mail client to filter messages using SpamSieve, please see Section 3 of the documentation available from the Help menu.
Make sure you train SpamSieve with both good messages and spam ones.
You’ve successfully started training SpamSieve. Keep training it with spam and good messages to build up the corpus and improve its accuracy.

SpamSieve’s corpus contains more good messages than spam messages. To make it more effective at catching spam, you can train it with some more spam messages. If around 65% of the messages in the corpus are spam, SpamSieve will be able to catch most incoming spam without incorrectly blocking any good messages.

SpamSieve’s corpus contains many more spam messages than good ones. To make it more effective at catching spam, you can train it with some more good messages. If around 65% of the messages in the corpus are spam, SpamSieve will be able to catch most incoming spam without incorrectly blocking any good messages.
SpamSieve’s corpus may be larger than necessary. To speed up SpamSieve and reduce its memory usage, you can use the Prune Corpus command to remove words from the corpus that are not being used.

SpamSieve’s corpus is larger than necessary. This makes it use more memory, and can potentially reduce its accuracy. If you are unhappy with SpamSieve’s accuracy, you can use the Reset Corpus command. Then retrain SpamSieve using 350 representative good messages and 650 spam messages that you have saved. This will often produce better results than the larger, more diluted corpus.

To improve SpamSieve’s accuracy, make sure that you correct it if it makes a mistake. If it marks a spam message as good, select the message and tell SpamSieve that it’s spam. If it marks a good message as spam, select the message and tell SpamSieve that it’s good.

SpamSieve’s message store file is damaged and could not be read. Please Control-click on this file:
/Users/<user>/Library/Application Support/SpamSieve/Corpus.corpus
and choose Show Package Contents. Then delete the MessageIDs file. This should allow you to use SpamSieve again without impacting its accuracy. You may want to run a disk repair program because a corrupt message store file is often a sign that the disk’s catalog structures are damaged.

SpamSieve’s word store file is damaged and could not be read. To continue and start a new corpus, you can rename the file
/Users/<user>/Library/Application Support/SpamSieve/Corpus.corpus
to CorpusOld.corpus and re-launch SpamSieve. You can also send this file to <spamsieve@c-command.com> to see whether it can be salvaged. The file corruption was most likely caused by damage to your disk’s catalog structures, so you may want to run a disk repair program so that other files are not corrupted in this way.
